      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To protect yourself from those hidden pitfalls, you need to be proactive, not reactive. You can't just hope the contract is fair; you have to make it so. When you see vagueness, treat it like a trap waiting to spring, because the Client's legal team will certainly try to interpret it in the way that benefits them—usually by making you pay.\n\nThe best defense against vague language is to demand absolute clarity on *everything*. If the contract says \"perform the Services,\" you must reply with, \"To ensure I meet your expectations and avoid any disputes, I need a detailed Statement of Work (SOW) that explicitly defines what 'Services' includes and, just as importantly, what it *excludes*.\" If they won't define the boundaries, you need to push back hard.\n\nIf the language is intentionally broad, like the indemnification clause itself, you can try to negotiate limitations. For example, you could propose limiting your liability to only the direct damages caused by your gross negligence, rather than *any* claim. This is a huge difference, and it's a negotiation point where you fight for your own skin.",
